      "content": "To address the memory limit issue, we'll use an iterative approach with a generator to yield nodes one by one, thus reducing memory usage. We can also use a deque for efficient queue management in BFS. Here's the code:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\nimport sys\n\ndef bfs(graph, start):\n    visited = set()\n    queue = deque([start])\n    while queue:\n        node = queue.popleft()\n        if node not in visited:\n            visited.add(node)\n            yield node\n            queue.extend(neighbor for neighbor in graph[node] if neighbor not in visited)\n\ndef shortest_path(graph, start, end):\n    path = []\n    queue = deque([(start, [start])])\n    while queue:\n        node, path = queue.popleft()\n        if node == end:\n            return path\n        for neighbor in graph[node]:\n            if neighbor not in path:\n                queue.append((neighbor, path + [neighbor]))\n\ndef main():\n    graph = {i: [] for i in range(10**6)}\n    for i in range(10**6):\n        for j in range(i + 1, 10**6):\n            graph[i].append(j)\n            graph[j].append(i)\n    \n    start",
